liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: A Navy dive team has recovered the black box from a MRH-90 Taipan helicopter involved in a fatal crash south of Hamilton Island. Captain Danniel Lyon, Lieutenant Maxwell Nugent, Warrant Officer Class Two Joseph Laycock and Corporal Alexander Naggs were killed when the helicopter ditched into the ocean during a training exercise late last month. In a statement, Defence says the Voice and Flight Data Recorder (VFDR) was recovered on Monday. "Defence’s priority remains the recovery of our soldiers and returning them to their families," the statement said. "Defence remains in close contact with the families and is updating them on the operation as new details become available." Defence support services: The Defence all-hours Support Line is a confidential telephone and online service for ADF members and their families 1800 628 036 Open Arms provides 24-hour free and confidential counselling and support for current and former ADF members and their families 1800 011 046 Soldier On is a national support services provider for Defence personnel, contemporary veterans, and their families. Contact during office hours 1300 620 380 Defence and Veterans Legal Service (DAVLS) can be contacted on 1800 33 1800

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Investigators have spoken with the mother of five young boys who were killed alongside their father in a house fire on Brisbane's bayside. liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: A stunning light display over Melbourne last night was most likely caused by remnants of a Russian rocket re-entering the atmosphere, Australia's space agency says. Here's the full statement from the Australian Space Agency: "The flashes of light seen across Melbourne skies overnight were likely the remnants of a Russian Soyuz-2 rocket re-entering the Earth's atmosphere. "Launch of the Soyuz-2 rocket occurred from Plesetsk Cosmodrome earlier in the evening. According to Russian authorities the launch placed a new generation 'GLONASS-K2' global navigation satellite into orbit. "This launch was notified and remnants of the rocket were planned to safely re-enter the atmosphere into the ocean off the south-east coast of Tasmania. "The Australian Space Agency will continue to monitor the outcomes of this re-entry with our Government partners."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Lights over Melbourne were likely caused by Russian rocket parts, authorities say

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The ASX 200 index has ended where it started the day. Despite a rise on Wall Street, confidence was dented after trade figures out of China showed a big fall in exports and imports last month. Myer (-14.1 per cent) had a bad day after investors did not like its weaker than expected profit forecast. James Hardie (+14.4 per cent)jumped after it forecast better than expected earnings and predicted an improving housing market in North America. While sales fell over the first quarter, profit margins were stronger. And coking coal miner Coronado Global Resources (-11.6 per cent) slumped after its net profit for the half year slumped by 65 per cent because of lower coal prices.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The traditional owners of the Juukan Gorge in the Pilbara in Western Australia say First Nations people are being put last by the WA government after the scrapping of new cultural heritage laws. Earlier today WA premier Roger Cook announced that a new law would be overturned after complaints by property owners and farmers. A 1972 cultural heritage law will be reinstated with amendments to allow Indigenous groups the right of appeal. The 2021 law was introduced in response to the destruction of sacred caves at Juukan Gorge by Rio Tinto in 2020 to expand an iron ore mine. The Puutu Kunti Kurrama and Pinikura Aboriginal Corporation say the Cook government's plan to repeal the laws demonstrates that Indigenous people and their culture are a low priority. PKKP land and heritage manager Dr Jordan Ralph says reverting to the outdated 1972 legislation is among the worst decisions for Aboriginal cultural heritage protection this  country has seen. “The PKKP are outraged that they, and traditional owners in Western Australia are back to  square one, and the Cook government is reverting to laws that allowed to destruction of Juukan  Gorge." “The safeguards that were supposed to be provided by the 2021 legislation have now been taken  away and we will revert back to an outdated definition of Aboriginal cultural heritage and an  approvals process that benefits industry over our country,” Dr Ralph says the PKKP has lost faith that the state's lawmakers can protect Indigenous sacred sites in WA. Here's more from Amelia Searson on aftermath of the destruction of 46,000 year old rock shelters at Juukan Gorge.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 'Among worst decisions for Aboriginal cultural heritage'

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Oil and gas producer Woodside Energy will sell a 10 per cent stake in its Scarborough liquefied natural gas project to LNG Japan for $US500 million. Woodside will hold a 90 per cent interest in the project and operate it. LNG Japan is a joint venture between Sumitomo Corp and Sojitz Corp. Woodside and LNG Japan have also agreed on the sale and purchase of 12 LNG cargoes a year for ten years starting in 2026. Scarborough, off the WA coast in the Carnarvon Basin, is Woodside's biggest growth project. Gas from Scarborough will feed Woodside's Pluto LNG plant and the first cargo is targeted for 2026. Woodside shares rose 0.6 per cent to $38.41.
